title: For Sale:  CIA 22 SURVIVAL RIFLE
postcontent: This is a very basic and handy 22LR single-shot survival rifle manufactured by various companies from around the turn of the century until the 1970s (when it was sold as the “Garcia Bronco”). This is an antique in good working condition, likely from the early 1950s, and has no markings other than the “Firearms International Corporation   Washington DC 20022” on the inside of the skeletonized buttplate. The Firearms International firm was begun in around 1952 as a front for the CIA to obtain and ship, through supposed commercial sales channels, surplus firearms to allies of the United States during the Cold War. After the Bay of Pigs fiasco, to which they apparently supplied the weapons, the company was outed and reorganized. They bought, imported, and sold many good guns from various manufacturers and this rifle may have been made by FN in Belgium, although there are no numbers or markings other than the importer info. Cool little survival rifle with a neat history. Face-to-face deals only and full refund if you are not happy with the rifle.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1943 Remington 1903A3 with bayonet, scabbard, and extras
postcontent:
This is a Remington 1903A3 with a 1943 serial number and barrel dated May 1943. It appears it has spent most of its life since WWII as a safe queen. The stock is extraordinary; there are no chips or cracks on the exterior or interior of the stock. The correct charthouses are present and clearly visible and the stock has beautiful tight wood grain. The bore is an absolutely pristine and shiny example of a two grooved barrel with no rust, marks, or frosting. The metal parts appear "R" stamped in the appropriate places.  Included with the rifle is a M1905 bayonet. Bayonet was manufactured and marked “RIA” (Rock Island Armory). The bayonet is dated 1907 with the appropriate serial number. The blade is 16" and has not been cut down or polished. The scabbard is a M1910 marked “AMC” and is dated 1917. Both are WWI and WWII survivors and attach and detach from the rifle easily.
The cleaning kit includes a numbered rubberized canvas bag, bore snake rope, complete take down cleaning rod and handle, US marked and serial numbered takedown tool, and metal oiler tube that fits in the buttstock. Also includes two removable front sight hoods used by the Marine Corps and two stripper clips. Sling is a new reproduction leather military sling.

title: For Sale:  W.J. & R.H. Scott Albany New York Percussion Rifle ANTIQUE American Sporting Gun .45 Cal Remington
postcontent: The hefty octagon barrel measures just over 32" long and features a small Nickel Silver blade front sight with a simple fixed iron rear sight. A 1 7/16" long Nickel Silver inlay on the top barrel flat is stamped "W. J. & R. H. SCOTT / ALBANY" while the name "REMINGTON" is discretely stamped on the left flat near the breech. Remington of course started out primarily as barrel manufacturers who would supply gun makers with quality barrels and/or actions. The lock and furniture are nicely engraved throughout, with the lock being marked "ALBANY". The barrel has a silvery appearance, likely having been lightly cleaned long ago, and appears to have a thin coat of varnish added. The lock and furniture retain a darker untouched patina. The stock features a coarsely checkered wrist and shows a pleasing untouched original finish. The name "C. E. SCOTT" is stamped under the buttstock just behind the triggerguard, likely a relative of the gun maker who made the stock. There is a fine 2" check on the left side of the buttstock forward of the buttplate and a 6 1/4" crack forward of the lock. Otherwise the wood is very sound with sharp, clean edges throughout. Engraved iron buttplate, toeplate, and triggerguard. The forward tip of the triggerguard is broken and missing with the rear tip having been repaired. Nickel Silver scroll lock screw escutcheon, wedge escutcheons, and Pewter forend cap. Ramrod pipes and rib appear to be brass and are original (pipes have been re-soldered). Original wood ramrod retains a threaded worm tip. The action functions very well and the nipple is a clean original. Overall a very nice and well marked example of a New York sporting rifle.
